-- Sub-Saharan African Equities Report: Fidelity Bank, KenolKobil, Scangroup
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-07-09T16:01:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-09/sub-saharan-african-equities-report-fidelity-bank-kenolkobil-scangroup.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rose to a
two-month high, climbing 0.4 percent to 1,665.6 at the close in
Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  advanced 0.1 percent to 74.76,
taking its increase this week to 0.7 percent, a third of gains.
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  retreated for a
third day, falling 0.8 percent to 24,566.99 in Lagos, the
commercial hub. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  rose for a
fourth day, rallying 0.3 percent to 758.79, while the  Ghana
Stock Exchange All-Share Index  fell for a fourth day, dropping
0.9 percent to 6,390.43, the lowest since April 22.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Fidelity Bank Plc  (FIDELITY NL), a Nigerian lender, rose 3
kobo, or 1.3 percent, to 2.34 naira, paring the weekly decline
to 6.4 percent. Fidelity is interested in buying one of the
banks bailed out by the West African nation last year, spokesman
 Emma Esinnah  said yesterday.  
 KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in seven African countries, advanced to the highest
since May 21, climbing 25 cents, or 2.4 percent to 10.65
shillings. KenolKobil said first-half results will be
“considerably” better than those reporter a year earlier,
according to a statement distributed by the Nairobi Stock
Exchange today.  
 Scangroup Ltd.  (SCAN KN), East Africa’ biggest marketing
company, rallied to a three-day high, rising 1 shillings, or 2.6
percent, to 39.75 shillings. Shareholders approved a dividend of
0.50 shilling a share for the year through December at the
company’s annual general meeting on June 29, the company said in
a statement dated yesterday and distributed by the Kenyan bourse
today.  
